    quickAnswerQuestion: 'What is the difference between Bettas and Gouramis?',
    quickAnswer:
      'Bettas and Gouramis are closely related labyrinth fish (suborder Anabantoidei), but they differ significantly in practice. Bettas (Betta splendens) are smaller (6–7 cm), more aggressive toward conspecifics, and are typically kept as solo fish in 5–10 gallon tanks — they come in hundreds of tail and colour varieties. Gouramis encompass a diverse family ranging from the 4 cm Sparkling Gourami to the 70 cm Giant Gourami, with most popular species (Dwarf, Pearl, Honey, Moonlight) being peaceful community fish suitable for 20–55 gallon tanks. Gouramis offer better community compatibility while Bettas offer more individual colour variety.',
