      'Yes, but freshwater stingrays (family Potamotrygonidae) are far more practical for home aquariums than saltwater species. Freshwater rays like the Motoro (Potamotrygon motoro) grow to 40–60 cm disc width, adapt well to captive conditions, and are available from specialist breeders for $100–$10,000+. Saltwater stingrays are rarely kept in home aquariums — most species grow too large (1–2+ metres), require massive marine systems with complex water chemistry, and are better suited to public aquaria. Both types are venomous and require experienced handling.',
